            "steps": "1. Recruit the participants and invite them over to the laboratory.\n2 Give them the following instructions: Each participant is paired with another (a computer program and whose sex was not revealed). Then, they independently solve 20 difficult trivia questions using a laptop. The questions are in multiple choice format, with four answer options. For each correct answer, a participant will earn 10 Japanese yen (10 US cents).\n3. Provide participants with a cover story: There are players 1 and 2. Player 1 is allowed to monitor the question that player 2 is currently working. When player 1 finds that player 2 happens to be working on the same question that he/she is working on, player 1 is allowed to click the hint button on the computer display. When player 1 clicks the hint button, two incorrect options will be automatically removed. On player 2's computer display, the colour changes from red to blue when player 1 chooses to monitor player 2. In the attention condition, the blue signal should appear with probability 0.80 per quiz (on average, in 16 out of 20 quizzes). In the no attention condition, the signal never turns blue.\n4. Assign all participants the role of player 2 in an apparently random manner. In addition, inform them that they had been assigned to the no hint condition, in which player 1 was still allowed to monitor\nplayer 2, but was not allowed to give hints (to dissociate player 1's monitoring behaviour (i.e., attention) from any potential benefit). \n5. Ask the participants to complete a questionnaire to assess their understanding of the task. No exclusion criteria are provided but in the study all participants correctly understood the task.\n6. Randomly assign the participants to either the attention or no attention condition and start the quiz.\n7. After completion apply post-task questionnaire containing four intimacy items: understanding (If you became friends with the partner, how well do you think this person would understand you?), validation (If you became friends with the partner, how much do you think this person would accept you?), caring (How much did the partner care for you?), and an additional reversed item corresponding to caring (How much do you agree that this partner had little concern for you?). Rate the items on a 7-point scale (1 = not at all to 7 = very much). Aggregate the items to one the intimacy score and compare the scores between attention and no-attention conditions using a t-test.",
